Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Reserve Judge Klossner presiding for Branch IV:  
case called at 8:55am. {MK]  
Defendant Felicia D Marshall in court with Attorney Sylvie Dahnert.  ADA Theresa Beck appears for the State of Wisconsin.

On Motion of the State, the Court amends the charge to Misdemeanor Battery, contrary to Statute 940.19(1).

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " No Contest " entered; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified (ADA Beck submits the victim impact statement); the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

The Court withholds sentence, and places Ms. Marshall on Probation for one year, with conditions:

--to participate in anger management or parenting classes if deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to obtain/maintain employment as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to pay costs of $243 plus the $200 DNA surcharge
The Court will schedule the issue of restitution for a hearing.

Days credit for time already served:  0 days
recess 9:16am.
